Package com.iontrading.mkv

Class MkvRecordset

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.iontrading.mkv.MkvObject
      • com.iontrading.mkv.MkvRecordset
  • @Keep
@KeepPublicClassMemberNames
public class MkvRecordset
extends MkvObject
    The MkvRecordset class wraps a ION Bus Recordset in a Java Object.

    A Recordset object allow to have a single object published on the ION Platform standing for multiple records without the need to publish these records as well; in addition to reduced usage of network and memory resources, support for Recordset allows for on demand supply of data on the publisher side. Since the publisher component is notified of every subscription requests hitting the Recordset, the mechanism allows for enforcement of entitlement and content-based entitlement on the publisher side.

    Recordset name are similar to records, without the name part, example: EUR.CM_DEPTH.BTEC.

    A MkvRecord matching the Recordset can be subscribed even without the record being publisher on the ION Platform.

    The subscribe interfaces to support this behavior are MkvSubscribeManager.persistentSubscribe(MkvRecordListener, MkvLifeCycleListener) MkvSubscribeManager.persistentSubscribe(MkvRecordListener, String[], MkvLifeCycleListener) that come with a standard update notifications via MkvRecordListener as well as a specific lifecycle listener via MkvLifeCycleListener that notifies the subscriber of the pertinent events for the status of the subscription.

    Records matching the Recordset can be supplied by the Publisher without the corresponding MkvRecord being created: the supplyRecord(String, MkvSupply) method can be used for record-less supplies.

    Unless otherwise noted, passing a null argument to a constructor or method in this class will cause a NullPointerException to be thrown.

    See Also:
    MkvObject, MkvRecordListener, MkvSupply, MkvSupplyFactory, MkvLifeCycleListener, MkvSubscriptionRequestListener, MkvSubscriptionRequest

    • Method Detail

      • setRouterToAcceptAllSubscriptions

        public void setRouterToAcceptAllSubscriptions()
        Allow the intermediate Router instances to automatically reply to the subscription requests, if they can. If the intermediate Router has the data requested by a subscriber, the Router is allowed to accept the subscription and send out the current snapshot, without involving the publisher again. Setting this flag will make the subscriptions via this Recordset be equal to regular record subscriptions, where intermediate Router can deliver data autonomously, even partially, without any publisher intervention. By doing so, the publisher contextually acknowledges that it will no longer be in control of each individual subscription request.

      • acceptSubscription

        public void acceptSubscription​(MkvSubscriptionRequest request,
                               MkvSupply snapshot)
        Accept a record subscription request that hit the Recordset. When creating a Recordset on publisher side, an optional MkvSubscriptionRequestListener object can be provided to programmatically react to record subscription requests matching the Recordset.

        To accept a request, the publisher code shall invoke the acceptSubscription(MkvSubscriptionRequest, MkvSupply) method, anytime and from any thread the business logic desire.

        To refuse a request, the publisher code shall invoke the rejectSubscription(MkvSubscriptionRequest, String) method, anytime and from any thread the business logic desire.

        Parameters:
        request - the object wrapping the subscription request for a record matching the Recordset
        snapshot - the snapshot supply with which the publisher wants to respond to the subscription request

      • rejectSubscription

        public void rejectSubscription​(MkvSubscriptionRequest request,
                               String errorMessage)
        Reject a record subscription request that hit the Recordset.

        When creating a Recordset on publisher side, an optional MkvSubscriptionRequestListener object can be provided to programmatically react to record subscription requests matching the Recordset.

        To accept a request, the publisher code shall invoke the acceptSubscription(MkvSubscriptionRequest, MkvSupply) method, anytime and from any thread the business logic desire.

        To refuse a request, the publisher code shall invoke the rejectSubscription(MkvSubscriptionRequest, String) method, anytime and from any thread the business logic desire.

        Parameters:
        request - the object wrapping the subscription request for a record matching the Recordset
        errorMessage - an optional error string reporting the business level reason why the subscription is being rejected

      • supplyRecord

        public void supplyRecord​(String recordName,
                         MkvSupply supply)
                  throws MkvObjectNotAvailableException,
                         MkvTypeNotFoundException,
                         MkvFieldNotFoundException,
                         MkvObjectNotLocalException,
                         MkvInvalidSupplyException
        This is an utility method for publisher side to provide incremental supplies over records without the corresponding MkvRecord object being published.
        Parameters:
        recordName - the name of the record to supply
        supply - the supply to emit
        Throws:
        MkvObjectNotAvailableException - if this MkvRecord is not available on the Platform.
        MkvTypeNotFoundException - if the type of this record is not available.
        MkvFieldNotFoundException - if a specified field is not part of this MkvRecord.
        MkvObjectNotLocalException - if this MkvRecord has not been created by this application.
        MkvInvalidSupplyException - if supply types don't match record types.

      • supplyRecordError

        public void supplyRecordError​(String recordName,
                              byte code,
                              String error)
                       throws MkvException
        This is an utility method for publisher side to provide incremental supplyy error over records without the corresponding MkvRecord object being published. It is typically used to notify a MkvRecordset.PSH_SUPPLY_NOT_AVAILABLE to Subscribers and have them handle the virtual unpublish of the record belonging to the Recordset.
        Parameters:
        recordName - the name of the record to supply
        code - the error code to emit
        error - the error message to emit
        Throws:
        MkvException - if this MkvRecord is not available on the Platform.
